jobs.description:
I was a management consultant in EY's Performance Improvement (PI) Advisory Practice, with a focus on IT, procurement and program management. 

I have worked for a number of EY clients including the Chief Information Officer Group (CIOG), Department of Human Services, Defence Materiel Organisation (DMO), the Department of Health and Ageing (renamed the Department of Health) as well as ACTEW Water. My engagement responsibilities have included:
o Liaising with the client and senior stakeholders as well as helping to facilitate workshops;
o Drafting stakeholder reports, media releases and creating Departmental wide communications;
o Reviewing government contract processes;
o For over 6 months, administrating and helping to manage a major government contract; 
o Researching legislative changes, legal requirements and their application; and
o Creating benefits and risk trackers.

From September 2014 to February 2015, I worked in EY's in-house legal team in Sydney (The General Counsel's Office) on secondment. In the time that I spent there, I undertook a range of legal work such as reviewing tender and employment contracts, conducting legal research and providing ad hoc legal advice on a variety of legal areas including employment law, commercial contracting and insurance.

In addition, I have also had the opportunity to work in New Zealand through a secondment role with EY's Wellington office.

general.description:
I am a solicitor specialising in technology, media and telecommunications transactions. Much of my work involves clients who are undertaking restructures or modernisation of their infrastructure and business systems. I am particularly interested in business transformation and love projects that use technology, data and process to solve problems and spur performance.

I advise a range of clients on a variety of commercial matters with particular focus on IT procurement, including:
• outsourcing arrangements; 
• systems development and implementation; 
• software maintenance and support; 
• data security; and 
• software-as-a-service. 

I also have significant experience in general procurement, IP and licensing, construction, infrastructure and general commercial transactions. 

I previously worked as an IT consultant, with a focus on implementing ITIL-compliant processes and deploying enterprise systems, including: 
• design and customisation of infrastructure monitoring solutions; 
• automated reporting on SLA compliance;
• data gathering and presentation;
• systems integration; and 
• systems design and implementation.

I am an experienced and skilled litigator and negotiator, primarily practising in personal and corporate insolvency and disputes relating to the provision of financial services. 

I have a broad commercial practice and also acted on behalf of disadvantaged people, who can not necessarily afford a lawyer on a pro bono basis. 

I provide candid and pragmatic advice to my clients in the management of disputes and seek to achieve the best commercial outcomes for them.

I regularly act for liquidators, administrators, receivers, creditors, companies and directors. 

Some of the matters that I have managed include:
- insolvent trading proceedings, either on behalf of the liquidator or director/s;
- voidable transactions, either on behalf of the liquidator or company being sued;
- bankruptcy related matters;
- disputes against financial advisers;
- contractual disputes;
- leasing disputes including retail and commercial; 
- professional negligence;
- restraint of trade disputes;
- trade practices disputes;
- franchising disputes;
- property related disputes, including building and construction disputes; and
- large scale litigation including worldwide discovery. 

I graduated from Monash University with a Bachelor of Laws and a Bachelor of Commerce (majoring in Accounting). I was admitted to practice in 2006.

I am a member of the Law Institute of Victoria, the Victorian Women Lawyers and the International Women's Insolvency and Restructuring Confederation.

